'''Shidori Jinja''' (倭文神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|de|Shinto Schrein|ja|神社|zh|神社|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Shizuoka Prefecture|de|Shizuoka Präfektur|ja|静岡県|zh|静冈县|12=draft}}, {{ill|Fujinomiya|de|Fujinomiya|ja|富士宮市|zh|富士宫市|12=draft}}. It is a {{ill|Shikinaisha|de|Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|zh|Shikinaisha|12=draft}} and its former {{ill|shrine rank|de|Schreinrang|ja|社格|zh|神社等级|12=draft}} was that of a {{ill|village shrine|de|Dorfschrein|ja|村社|zh|村社|12=draft}}.

==History==
In the '''{{ill|Engishiki|de|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|zh|Engishiki|12=draft}}''' (Vol. 9, Shingi 9), Shidori Jinja is recorded as one of the '''{{ill|Fuji District, Shizuoka|de|Drei Schreine des Fuji-Distrikts|ja|富士郡|zh|富士郡|Fuji District, Shizuoka=Fuji District, Shizuoka|lt=Three shrines of Fuji District|12=draft}}''' and is identified as the same shrine. Also, in the same ''Engishiki'' (Vol. 24, Shukei section), “thirty-one bolts of woven textile (倭文卅一端)” are listed among Suruga Province’s tribute items, suggesting that the local 倭文部 (Shitori-be) lived in this area. In the Middle Ages, the local Suruga power '''{{ill|Fuji clan|de|Fuji Klan|ja|富士氏|zh|富士氏|12=draft}}''' is said to have worshipped here.<ref>
岡田米夫、『日本史小百科 神社』、近藤出版、1977年、146頁
</ref>

